observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE:
a. Instruct the Inventory Committee to follow the guidelines and procedures as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of those found at station and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality;
b. Ensure compliance with the prescribed procedures for the proper disposition of unserviceable properties;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to: (1) maintain PPELCs to support the recorded PPE items and facilitate the reconciliation between the accounting and property records, (2) reclassify or derecognize all tangible items below the capitalization threshold from the PPE account, and (3) submit a complete and accurate lapsing schedule to substantiate the balances of the Accumulated Depreciation and Depreciation Expense accounts; and
d. Require the Municipal Assessor to secure the necessary documents to support the ownership claims of the Municipality over the purchased land costing ₱10,000,000.00.

We recommended that the LCE enforce the collection of these taxes, and:
a. Require the Municipal Treasurer to exert more efforts to collect from the taxpayers and for those who have been unable to pay their taxes for several years, issue notices of delinquency for them to settle their unpaid taxes;
b. If circumstances so warrant, avail of the Civil remedies provided for by the provisions of the Local Government Code (RA 7160), specifically Sections 174 to 176 thereof. Section 174 provides for the civil remedies which are by (a) administrative action through distraint of personal properties and (b) by judicial actions. Section 175 provides for the procedure on the distraint of personal property and Section 176 provides for the levy of Real Properties.
